To remove an item from an array in JavaScript, you can use the `filter()` method. Here's an example code snippet to demonstrate how to remove an item from an array:

```javascript
function removeItemFromArray(arr, itemToRemove) {
  return arr.filter(function(item) {
    return item!== itemToRemove;
  });
}
```

This `removeItemFromArray` function takes an array (`arr`) and an item to remove (`itemToRemove`) as input and returns a new array with the specified item removed.

Here's how you can use this function to remove an item from an array:

```javascript
var originalArray = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
var itemToRemove = 3;
var newArray = removeItemFromArray(originalArray, itemToRemove);
console.log(newArray);  // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

In this example, the `removeItemFromArray` function is called with `originalArray` and `itemToRemove` as arguments, and the resulting new array with the item removed (`[1, 2, 4, 5]`) is stored in the `newArray` variable.

Finally, the `console.log` statement outputs the new array to the console.

To generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document, you can use the `hyperref` and `tocloft` packages. Here's an example of how you can implement this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\newpage

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section of your document. It provides an overview of the content and purpose of the document.

\section{Methodology}
In this section, you will describe the methodology used to complete the project or research. This may include details about the tools, techniques, and steps taken.

\section{Results}
Here, you will present the results of your project or research. This section should be detailed and include relevant data, charts, and figures.

\section{Conclusion}
Finally, you will summarize the main findings and conclusions from your project or research. This section should provide closure and tie together the key points from the previous sections.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the necessary packages are loaded and the `\tableofcontents` command is used to create the table of contents. The sections are created using the `\section` command, and the table of contents automatically updates as you add more sections to your document.

To customize the appearance of the table of contents, you can use the `tocloft` package with options like `\renewcommand{\cftsecfont}{\large\bfseries}` to change the font size and style of the section titles in the table of contents.

Make sure you have the necessary packages installed in your LATEX distribution, and you can use this example as a starting point to create an automated table of contents in your document.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, you can make use of the `chessboard` package. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do it:

1. First, include the `chessboard` package in the preamble of your LaTeX document. Add the following line to your preamble:

```latex
\usepackage{chessboard}
```

2. Next, you can use the `begin{chessboard}` command to start drawing the chessboard, and `end{chessboard}` command to finish drawing it. Inside the `chessboard` environment, you can use various commands to set the position of the pieces on the board. For example, to place a pawn at the position "e2", you can use the `\setlegalmoves` command as follows:

```latex
\setlegalmoves{e2}{pawn}
```

3. Repeat the above step to place all the required pieces on the board. Here's an example of how to place all the pieces on the board using the `chessboard` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\begin{document}

\begin{chessboard}
\setlegalmoves{a7}{rook}
\setlegalmoves{b7}{knight}
\setlegalmoves{c7}{bishop}
\setlegalmoves{d7}{queen}
\setlegalmoves{e7}{king}
\setlegalmoves{f7}{bishop}
